Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Paraguay has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19). For information on how to return to the UK from Paraguay, see Return to the UK
These regulations are subject to change and the situation is changing rapidly. You should follow the instructions of the Paraguayan authorities as new measures may be brought in with short notice.
For information on how to return to the UK from Paraguay, see Return to the UK
Borders and travel
All passenger flights have been suspended until further notice. Borders will remain closed until at least 26 April.
Those who arrive in Paraguay must comply with the self-isolation requirement for 14 days.
Immigration
Due to travel restrictions, the Paraguayan immigration authorities have automatically extended the 90-day permission for tourists and non-residents to stay in Paraguay from 13 March onwards, for the duration of the emergency.
You can find more information on the Paraguayan Dirección General de Migraciones website (in Spanish).
Local measures
Paraguayan authorities have declared a nationwide health-related State of Emergency.
Measures include:
a ban on all non-essential movement nationwide until 26 April. There are exceptions to buy food, go to the pharmacy or hospital and for key workers. Stay in your accommodation unless absolutely necessary to go out.
the temporary closure of schools, universities and public parks
the cancellation of mass events and gatherings (public and private) such as at cinemas, concerts and conventions, as well as religious, sports, leisure and political activities
a requirement to wear a face mask in public, including on public transport, throughout Paraguay
From 13 April, new restrictions for private vehicles apply nationwide:
Vehicles with plates ending in 0, 2, 4, 6, 8 can only use the road on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays
Vehicles with plates ending in 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 can only use the road on Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and Sundays
If you’re in Paraguay, follow the advice of the Paraguayan authorities.
Health
If you present symptoms, you should contact the Paraguayan Ministry of Health at 154 / 911 or INERAM hospital at (021) 290 838.
People who have tested positive for COVID-19 and do not need to be admitted to hospital, will stay in specialised shelters. This includes the following:
Those who would like to do so voluntarily
Those in vulnerable situations whose accommodation is not suitable for self-isolation (because it is crowded and/or small)
Those who have broken self-isolation
Those who have come from abroad and tested positive during their quarantine period
Further information
Further information is also available on the Paraguayan Ministry of Health website or official Twitter channel (both in Spanish).
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
You can find more information about cases in Paraguay on the TravelHealthPro country page.
